Density Curves

Histograms are always a great place to start. However, binning is can be an issue, especially with small sample sizes. It is sometimes easier to visualize the distribution by plotting the data with emprical density curve. These are basically histograms that have been smoothed using a kernel function. Here gaussian smoothing is employed, it is the default. There is one colored curve for each of the 10 samples. The black curve gives the pooled density. A series of simple horizontal boxplots is also plotted below for comparison. For brevity, the boxplot code is hidden.

frames = c(seq(0.01, 0.2, 0.02), rep(0.2, 12), seq(0.2, 0.01, -0.02), rep(0.01, 12))
df <- melt(data)
for(i in frames){
  p <- ggplot(df, aes(value)) + geom_density(fill = "black")
  p <- p + xlim(min(df$value), max(df$value)) + theme_bw() + theme(legend.position="none")
  p <- p + geom_density(aes(value, fill=variable), alpha = i)
  print(p)
}

Maximum Likelihood Estimators

The function below provides stable maximum likelihood parameter estimates for the following distributions:

  • unif : uniform
  • norm : normal
  • lnorm : 2-parameter lognormal
  • lnorm3 : 3-parameter lognormal
  • exp : 1-parameter exponential
  • gamma : 2-parameter gamma
  • gamma3 : 3-parameter gama
  • weibull : weibull
  • gumbel : gumbel
  • gev : generalized extreme value
library(fitdistrplus)
library(ordinal)
library(evd)
library(FAdist)

stable = c("unif", "norm", "lnorm", "lnorm3", "exp", "gamma", "gamma3", "weibull", "gumbel", "gev")

# Enforce evd namespace since there are multiple gev functions at play.
pgev = evd::pgev; rgev = evd::rgev; dgev = evd::dgev; qgev = evd::qgev

mleFit <- function(name, x){
  fit <- switch(name,
                lnorm3 = {
                  fitdist(x, name, start = list(
                    shape = log((mean(x)^2) / sqrt(var(x) + mean(x))),
                    scale = log(1+(var(x)/(mean(x)^2))),
                    thres = -0.1))
                  },
                gamma3 = {
                  fitdist(x, name, start = list(
                    shape = mean(x)^2 / var(x),
                    scale = var(x) / mean(x),
                    thres = -0.1))
                  },
                gumbel = {
                  fitdist(x, "gev", start = as.list(fgev(df$value)$estimate[1:2]), 
                          fix.arg = list(shape = 0))
                  },
                gev = {
                  fitdist(x, name, start = as.list(fgev(df$value)$estimate))
                  },
                exp2 = {
                  fitdist(x, name, start = list(
                    rate = 1 / mean(x), 
                    thres = -5))
                  },
                {
                  fitdist(x, name)
                  }
                )
  }

Comparative Density Curves

Utilizing the MLE estimator function developed above, we can plot the empirical and theoretical density curves against one another.

doubleDensity <- function(name){
  fit <- mleFit(name = name, x = df$value)
  parameters <- c(as.list(fit$estimate))
  #parameters <-  c(as.list(fit$estimate), as.list(fit$fix.arg))
  interval <- seq(0, 30, 0.01)
  density <- do.call(paste("d", name, sep=""), c(list(x=interval), as.list(parameters))) 
  p <- ggplot(df, aes(value)) + geom_density(fill = "black", alpha = 0.5)
  p <- p + ylim(0, 0.12) + xlim(min(df$value), max(df$value)) + theme_bw()
  p <- p + annotate("ribbon", x = interval, ymax = density, 
                    ymin = 0, fill = "#E69F00", col = "#E69F00", alpha = 0.5)
  p <- p + annotate("text", x = 18, y = 0.075, label = paste(name, "distribution"), size=10)
  print(p)
  p
}

dd <- lapply(stable, doubleDensity)
library(gridExtra); grid.arrange(dd[[4]],  dd[[7]], dd[[8]], dd[[9]],nrow = 2)

L-moments in R

Revising the ‘lmon’ Package

The lmom package for R is developed an maintained by Jonathan Hosking at IMB Research. The package is very powerful and straight forward to use. It computes both empirical and theoretical L-moments and includes functions for plotting L-moment ratio diagrams. However the lmom package only provides an interface for producing L-Kurtosis vs. L-Skew moment ratio diagrams. This limits the utility for determining sample data fits to lower-order distributions. I augmented the lmon library to fit 2-parameter distributions, with the hope that it can become its own CRAN package, or merged with the offiical lmon library.

L-CV vs. L-Skew

After Vogel and Wilson 1996, relationships between L-CV and L-Skew can be developed for several two-parameter distributions as shown below.

t3 = seq(-1, 1, 0.01)
LN2 = 1.16008*t3 - 0.05325*t3^2 - 0.10501*t3^4 - 0.00103*t3^6
GA2 = 1.74139*t3 - 2.59736*t3^2 + 2.09911*t3^4 - 0.35948*t3^6
WB2 = 0.17864 + 1.02381*t3 - 0.17878*t3^2 - 0.00894*t3^4 - 0.01443*t3^6
GP2 = 0.33299 + 0.44559*t3 + 0.16641*t3^2 + 0.09111*t3^5 - 0.03625*t3^7

out = data.frame(
  tau_3 = t3,
  LN2 = LN2,
  GA2 = GA2,
  WB2 = WB2,
  GP2 = GP2)

The Bootstrap

m = 10000; n = 25
resample <- function(i) df$value[floor(runif(n, 1, 250))]


bootstrap = lapply(1:m, resample)
lmr <- lapply(bootstrap, samlmu, 4)
lmr <- matrix(unlist(lmr), nrow = 4, 
              dimnames=list(c("l_1", "l_2", "t_3", "t_4"), NULL))
lmrd2.p <- function(x){
  lmrd2(x, main = "L-moment Ratio Diagram :: L-CV vs. L-Skew",
     lwd = 2, col = rep("#44444444", 10),
     pch.data = 19, cex.data = 0.1, 
     xlegend = 0.5, ylegend=0.2)
}

for(i in 1:(m/1000)) lmrd2.p(t(lmr[,1:(i*1000)]))
L.cv <- lmr[2,] / lmr[1,]
L.sk <- lmr[3,]
d <- kde2d(L.sk, L.cv)

for(i in 1:10){
    lmrd2.p(t(lmr[,1:(m-i)]))
  
    contour(d, drawlabels=FALSE, nlevels=7, lwd=3,
        col=c("#999999", "#56B4E9", "#009E73", "#F0E442", "#0072B2", "#D55E00", "#CC79A7"), add=TRUE)

    #abline(v=c(mean(L.sk), median(L.sk)), h=c(mean(L.cv), median(L.cv)), lwd=2, lty=c(1,2))
}
